  "prompt": "How does a fingerprint scanner work on a smartphone?",
  "response": "There are two main types of fingerprint scanners used in smartphones:\n\n1. Optical Scanners:\n- Use a digital camera to capture an image of the fingerprint\n- Light is shined onto the finger and a camera takes a detailed photograph\n- Good for surface-level detail, less secure and slower\n\n2. Capacitive Scanners (more common):\n- Use electrical conductivity to map fingerprint details\n- Small electrical sensors detect the ridges and valleys of a fingerprint\n- When a finger touches the sensor, the ridges and valleys create different electrical charges\n- These variations are converted into a digital map of the fingerprint\n- More secure and faster than optical scanners\n\nModern smartphones often use advanced capacitive scanners like:\n- Capacitive touch sensors embedded in the screen\n- Side-mounted fingerprint sensors\n- Under-display scanners that work through the screen\n\nThe scanner creates a unique digital template of the fingerprint during initial setup, which is securely stored and used for comparison during future authentication attempts.\n\nThe technology allows quick, secure access to the device and can also be used for app authentication and mobile payments.",
